Aren’t these the cutest Gigg(LE) Gnomes!?

Teach the /-le/ sound, have students help you make a list of -le words & solidify learning with this simple yet festive craftivity. 

Follow this format to create the writing on the hats —> “My gnome giggles when _________.” 

Ex.) My gnome giggles when he is tickled. My gnome giggles when he plays the fiddle. My gnome giggles when he tells a riddle. My gnome giggles when he eats pickles.

Not just for teachers! Want to engage your kids over break? Have them make it with you! ☃️

1 cup flour
6 TBSP salt
2 tsp. Cream of tartar
1 TBSP veg. oil
1 Cup warm water
* Food Coloring
* Essential Oil
* Glitter

1. Mix dry ingredients in med. sauce pan

2. Add wet ingredients & stir until everything is mixed 

3. Cook over med. heat continually stirring until dough isn’t sticky. It will start to pull away from the pan

4. Remove from pan. When cool to touch, knead until completely cool

Ok but in all seriousness….it’s possible for anyone to become a children’s book author!

Here are the 3 main steps:

1️⃣ Idea generation. Come up with an idea that you can turn into a story. Am idea you can use to make a point or teach a lesson.

2️⃣ Write + Edit. Don’t stop until you are happy with what you have! A good story is COHESIVE AND CLEAR! If you have a great basis but need help editing to the finish line, reach out to people you know, look for an established freelance editor, or work with a writing + publishing coach.

3️⃣ Publish! You can either go the traditional route or the self publishing route! Dm me if you want to know more about self publishing.

There’s obviously a lot more that goes into the process, but that is the framework! Follow along to learn more about writing + self publishing children’s books 💖

Learn about your publishing options 👇

📖 Traditional Publishing Route
• Write a query letter 
• Write a manuscript
• Find an agent 
• Try to get the agent to read your manuscript 
• Repeat above steps if rejected (all before even beginning the publishing process)

📖 Self Publishing Route
• No query letter needed
• No agent needed
• Find someone who can offer you guidance and support through the writing process & or publishing process (Me!! 🙋🏼‍♀️)
• Breathe easy knowing you’ll only have to go through the process one time (unless you write another book 😉)

Follow along if you want more writing + publishing tips 😘

My pre-author life seems light years away….

A friend of mine said to me the other day “How did you get to this point? You’re literally radiating happiness. Do you remember a few years ago we were sitting in Moes & you were on the brink of tears bc you had no idea what you wanted to do with your life? Now we’re sitting here & not only have you accomplished SO much but you’re going even further and helping other people do the same…” 

I guess my take away here is this:

1. Take time to stop and really think about how far you’ve come. 
Even if you’re not where you want to be yet, celebrate the growth you have made. I promise you, it will inspire you to keep growing. 

2. Take that leap of faith. TRUST yourself. Take that painting class, sign up for the dance class, WRITE THAT BOOK YOU’VE BEEN DREAMING OF. 

3. Invest in yourself. Know that you don’t have to go it alone. There are experts out there in every field that can help you make your dreams a reality. Find someone you connect with and GO FOR IT. You CAN do it.
 
Lastly, 
If that thing you feel compelled to do is learn to dance, I absolutely can not help you there 😅 (ask my friends, they’ll confirm)

HOWEVER,
If that thing you feel compelled to do is write a book, I can be your support in making that a reality for you ❤️‍🔥 If you have questions, DM me. If you’re ready to get the show on the road, book a 1:1 with me in my bio link.

That’s all for now folks, love u 💖

Being realistic is sooooo last year 💅 It’s so much easier to accomplish great things with a “shoot for the stars” mindset. 

When I was writing my first book my mom asked if I’d be upset if it only sold 20 copies to friends and family. I laughed and said “nah it’s been a cool experience either way.” (Although admittedly I would’ve been kind of bummed if that was the case 😅)

Months later I became a best selling author & my whole world changed.

Years later, I now help other people bring THEIR book dreams to life and I couldn’t love it more.

The decision to write and publish my first book despite the possibility of failure has led me down the most beautiful path. A path full of amazing humans, incredible opportunities and once in a life time experiences. 

So I guess my point is, if you have been dreaming of becoming an author, or have a book idea you’ve been wanting to turn into a REAL BOOK….This is your sign to do it.

I can be your guidance and support 💖Message me if you have questions about starting your publishing journey or want me to point you in the right direction.

& one more for the road……it’s only delusional until it’s done, so let’s get a move on!

Self publishing is ABSOLUTELY as legitimate as traditional publishing. & don’t let anyone tell you otherwise.

I am literally sitting in my home right now that I was only able to purchase BECAUSE I self published my books. 

YES, self publishing can be daunting, but it can also be immensely rewarding and fun if you learn the ropes. 

My top 2 favorite things about self publishing:

1️⃣ You retain autonomy over all of the decisions surrounding your book. 
2️⃣ You are in control of the publishing timeline & can make it happen as quickly or slowly as you want. 

If you’re ready to self publish your book, DM ME!!!!!! Let’s get you going 😆

Why do the the “easy to care for” plants seem harder to care for than the “hard to care for” plants. Now that i’ve planted the seed (pun intended) all we can do is wait for the next 3AM burst of energy where I wake up & write the whole book in my phone notes 🤪📖🌿

Laundry is my least favorite chore…..why does it take so long. It’s literally like a 5 day event. You put the clothes in the washer. You forget about them for a day so then you have to re-wash them. Then you have to remember to actually switch them over to the dryer this time. Then once they’re dry you take them out and they have to sit in the basket for a day or two (mandatory). When you go to fold them they’re wrinkly but you don’t care at that point. & then maybe some of them get put away if you don’t wear them first?? & by the time you finish, it’s time to re-wash them again. Wow. Anyways, I hope laundry goes differently for you.

No seriously, let yourself enjoy the experience…or else.

8 ways to do this:

1. Set aside special times to write, even if it’s a 10 minute block. Intently focus on your book during that time. 

2. Actively choose to take a break if you need one, let yourself breathe, and come back when you’re ready. & don’t you dare even think about your book during your break.

3. Be present when you are writing. Stop and look around at the coffee shop. Close your eyes and really taste the next sip of your chai latte. Being preset enhances creativity and clarity. 

4. If you do want to have your book published by a certain date, set achievable goals.

5. Join an accountability group (there are tons on Facebook.)

6. Take a course to keep you on track (I offer one that takes you through the entire process from start to finish.)

7. Hire a coach to lead you through the process. 

8. Remind yourself that it’s absolutely, positively, not that serious.

Inspired by my late grandfather, Pops.

He loved making pancakes and talking about the weather. He loved admiring how life is a rollercoaster, full of ups and downs. He loved to wax his Cadillac (and your car, and your friends car, and the neighbors car-even if they weren’t Cadillacs.) And he loved to remind me that, at the end of the day, life is good 💜

But life is also short, so do what makes you happy, whatever that may be.

& just like that, the “elementary school teacher” chapter comes to an end…at least for now. 

I could attempt to put into words how much teaching has meant to me the past 6 years…the lifelong friends, fearless/hilarious/inspiring students, happy memories, self growth etc. etc. but then we’d be here for far too long. 

Anyways, I think I’ll always find myself in some sort of teaching role (moth to a flame vibes - a revelation conversation with @aenygren ), but being an elementary teacher has been so incredibly special. Shout out to teachers, you all are the absolute realest, most passionate human beings on the face of this earth.

& shout out to the teacher who makes this classroom their second home- I hope you enjoy the bookshelf wallpaper as much as I did 📚💙

On to the next chapter! 📖

#1 Read extensively in the genre you want to write in

When I was younger I worked at a banquet hall. As I was working a wedding one night, rushing around with my tray to collect glasses, a wedding guest stopped me, looked me dead in the eyes, and said “slow down, life moves so fast.”

Little did I know I’d reflect on that moment A LOT in the coming years. For whatever reason, their words forced me into an utterly present state - you know, one of those moments that you remember so clearly years later, and you’re not sure why, because it seems rather small in the grand scheme of things. 

I’m not sure if it was because they were a experiencing a “woah” moment that those big life events tend to bring about and they just felt the need to share it with the nearest person, or if it was something else entirely. I’m not sure if it actually had anything to do with me at all.

But, I’m glad it stopped 15 year old me in my tracks, because it really is so clarifying to slow down and trust that you’ll be everything you need to be in time.

Teaching brought me SO MUCH. So much knowledge (about others, collaboration, education, life, & myself), so much joy, so much growth, so many friends, and of course a few tears. 

I LOVED teaching. I’ve loved every student I’ve ever had beyond words. I loved the art of teaching. I loved the energy of a classroom and being constantly surrounded by growth. I loved feeling my eyes brim with happy tears when a student had that AHA moment or used a strategy to regulate themselves or de-escalate a situation 🥲

However, at the end of the day, the education system was not a sustainable realm for me to exist in for several reasons (none of which had to with my kiddos,) but we can get into that another time.

I do know though, that I wouldn’t change a thing. Every twist and turn in my journey has led me to where I am now. Teaching kickstarted my author journey & helped me uncover my passion for writing & publishing children’s books. & now I get to share both my books and my publishing knowledge to help others bring their incredible children’s books into the world too. Books the world needs to see ❤️

Shout out to every single teacher out there, whether I know you personally or not. Love your kiddos, but stand your ground with the education system as much as you can! & hit me up if you ever want to publish a book 📖🥰
